  <!-- Article Header -->
  <header class="article-header bg-blue-50 py-12">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto text-center">
        <h1 class="text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-bold mb-6 text-gray-900">Recognizing Early Signs of Autism: A Guide for New Hampshire Parents</h1>
        <p class="text-xl text-gray-700 mb-8">Understanding developmental milestones and when to seek professional evaluation for your toddler</p>
        <div class="flex items-center justify-center space-x-6 text-sm text-gray-600">
          <span>By Moving Mountains ABA Team</span>
          <span>•</span>
          <span>January 15, 2024</span>
          <span>•</span>
          <span>8 min read</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- Article Content -->
  <article class="article-content py-16">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto prose prose-lg">
        <section class="mb-12">
          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">As a parent in New Hampshire, you want the best for your child's development. If you're noticing differences in how your toddler communicates, plays, or interacts with others, you may be wondering about autism spectrum disorder (ASD). Recognizing early signs of autism can be crucial for accessing timely intervention services that can significantly impact your child's development.</p>
          
          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">At Moving Mountains ABA, we work with families throughout New Hampshire to provide comprehensive evaluations and evidence-based ABA therapy services. This guide will help you understand early autism signs, developmental milestones, and when to consider seeking professional evaluation.</p>
          
          <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-6 my-8">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-blue-800">Important Note</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-700">Every child develops at their own pace, and having one or two of these signs doesn't necessarily mean your child has autism. However, if you notice several of these behaviors persisting over time, it may be worth discussing with your pediatrician or contacting an ABA therapy provider for evaluation.</p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Common Early Signs of Autism (Ages 12-24 months)</h2>
          
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
            <div class="sign-category">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-800">Social Communication</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-gray-700">
                <li><strong>Limited eye contact:</strong> Doesn't make or maintain eye contact during interactions or play</li>
                <li><strong>Doesn't respond to name:</strong> May not turn when their name is called, even when not distracted</li>
                <li><strong>Limited gestures:</strong> Doesn't wave bye-bye, point to request items, or show objects to others</li>
                <li><strong>Unusual communication patterns:</strong> May not babble by 12 months or use single words by 16 months</li>
                <li><strong>Lack of joint attention:</strong> Doesn't follow your point or bring objects to share interest with you</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="sign-category">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-800">Social Interaction</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-gray-700">
                <li><strong>Limited social smiling:</strong> Doesn't smile back when you smile at them by 6 months</li>
                <li><strong>Doesn't engage in peek-a-boo:</strong> Shows little interest in simple social games</li>
                <li><strong>Preference for solitude:</strong> Seems to prefer playing alone and may not seek comfort when upset</li>
                <li><strong>Limited imitation:</strong> Doesn't copy your actions, sounds, or facial expressions</li>
                <li><strong>Difficulty with back-and-forth play:</strong> Struggles with turn-taking in simple games</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="sign-category">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-800">Play and Behavior</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-gray-700">
                <li><strong>Repetitive behaviors:</strong> Hand flapping, rocking, spinning, or other repetitive movements</li>
                <li><strong>Unusual play patterns:</strong> Lines up toys, focuses on parts of objects, or plays the same way repeatedly</li>
                <li><strong>Sensory sensitivities:</strong> Over- or under-reaction to sounds, textures, lights, or other sensory input</li>
                <li><strong>Rigid routines:</strong> Becomes upset when routines are changed or interrupted</li>
                <li><strong>Limited pretend play:</strong> Doesn't engage in pretend play appropriate for their age</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="sign-category">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-800">Communication Development</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-gray-700">
                <li><strong>Delayed language development:</strong> Not meeting typical language milestones</li>
                <li><strong>Loss of previously learned skills:</strong> Stops using words or skills they previously had</li>
                <li><strong>Echolalia:</strong> Repeats words or phrases without apparent meaning</li>
                <li><strong>Difficulty following simple instructions:</strong> Struggles to follow one-step directions</li>
                <li><strong>Limited requesting:</strong> Doesn't ask for help or desired items appropriately</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Red Flags at Different Ages</h2>
          
          <div class="space-y-8">
            <div class="age-milestone bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-lg">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-red-700">By 12 Months</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                <li>No babbling or pointing by 12 months</li>
                <li>No single words by 16 months</li>
                <li>No two-word phrases by 24 months</li>
                <li>No response to name by 12 months</li>
                <li>Loss of any language or social skills at any age</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="age-milestone bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-lg">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-red-700">By 18 Months</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                <li>Doesn't point to request or show interest</li>
                <li>Doesn't engage in pretend play</li>
                <li>Avoids or dislikes physical affection</li>
                <li>Doesn't follow simple one-step instructions</li>
                <li>Unusual attachment to objects</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="age-milestone bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-lg">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-red-700">By 24 Months</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                <li>Doesn't use two-word meaningful phrases</li>
                <li>Doesn't imitate actions or words</li>
                <li>Doesn't follow two-step instructions</li>
                <li>Doesn't walk steadily or has lost motor skills</li>
                <li>Significant regression in any area</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">When to Consider Professional Evaluation in New Hampshire</h2>
          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">If you're noticing several of the signs mentioned above, or if your parental instinct is telling you something might be different about your child's development, it's worth seeking a professional evaluation. Early identification and intervention can make a significant difference in outcomes.</p>
          
          <div class="evaluation-criteria bg-yellow-50 border-l-4 border-yellow-400 p-6 my-8">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-yellow-800">Consider Evaluation If:</h3>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
              <li>Your child has missed multiple developmental milestones</li>
              <li>You've noticed a loss of previously acquired skills</li>
              <li>Your pediatrician has expressed concerns about development</li>
              <li>Teachers or childcare providers have mentioned concerns</li>
              <li>Your child's behavior is significantly different from peers</li>
              <li>You have a family history of autism or developmental delays</li>
              <li>Your parental instinct tells you something is different</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">Types of Professionals Who Can Help</h3>
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
            <div class="professional-type">
              <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-blue-800">Developmental Pediatricians</h4>
              <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">Medical doctors specializing in developmental issues who can provide comprehensive evaluations and diagnoses.</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Available at: Dartmouth-Hitchcock, Elliot Health System</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="professional-type">
              <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-blue-800">Board Certified Behavior Analysts (BCBAs)</h4>
              <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">Specialists in behavior analysis who can conduct functional assessments and provide ABA therapy services.</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Available at: Moving Mountains ABA and other ABA providers</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="professional-type">
              <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-blue-800">Child Psychologists</h4>
              <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">Mental health professionals who specialize in childhood development and can provide comprehensive psychological evaluations.</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Available through private practice and hospital systems</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="professional-type">
              <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-blue-800">Early Intervention Teams</h4>
              <p class="text-gray-700 mb-2">Multidisciplinary teams that provide evaluations and services for children under 3 through NH's Early Supports & Services program.</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Contact: Family Centered Early Supports & Services</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">How Early ABA Intervention Helps</h2>
          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">Applied Behavior Analysis (ABA) therapy has decades of research supporting its effectiveness for children with autism spectrum disorders. When implemented early, ABA intervention can help children develop crucial skills and reduce challenging behaviors.</p>
          
          <div class="benefits-grid grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
            <div class="benefit-item">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3 text-green-700">Communication Development</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-700">ABA therapy can help children develop verbal and non-verbal communication skills, including requesting, labeling, and social communication.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="benefit-item">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3 text-green-700">Social Skills Building</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-700">Teaching appropriate social interactions, play skills, and peer relationships through structured learning and practice.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="benefit-item">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3 text-green-700">Adaptive Behavior Skills</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-700">Building independence in daily living skills such as toileting, feeding, dressing, and following routines.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="benefit-item">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3 text-green-700">Challenging Behavior Reduction</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-700">Identifying the function of challenging behaviors and teaching appropriate replacement behaviors.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="research-highlight bg-green-50 border-l-4 border-green-500 p-6 my-8">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-green-800">Research Shows:</h3>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
              <li>Children receiving early intensive ABA therapy show significant improvements in IQ, language, and adaptive behavior</li>
              <li>Up to 47% of children receiving intensive early ABA achieve intellectual and educational functioning within the normal range</li>
              <li>Early intervention (before age 3) typically leads to better long-term outcomes</li>
              <li>ABA therapy can reduce the need for special education services later in life</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">New Hampshire Resources for Autism Evaluation</h2>
          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">New Hampshire offers several resources for families seeking autism evaluations and early intervention services:</p>
          
          <div class="resources-grid grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
            <div class="resource-category">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-800">Early Intervention (Ages 0-3)</h3>
